{"cells": [{"cell_type": "markdown", "metadata": {}, "source": ["# Planet Mass Calculator\n", "\n", "## Introduction to Newton's Universal Law of Gravitation\n", "\n", "Newton’s Universal Law of Gravitation states that every mass attracts every other mass in the universe. The force of attraction is directly proportional to the product of their masses and inversely proportional to the square of the distance between their centers. This principle is crucial for understanding how celestial bodies interact with each other.\n", "\n", "## Calculating Planet Masses\n", "\n", "Using the formula:\n", "[ F = G \\frac{m_1 m_2}{r^2} ]\n", "where:\n", "- F is the gravitational force.\n", "- G is the gravitational constant.\n", "- m_1 and m_2 are the masses of the two objects.\n", "- r is the distance between the centers of the two masses.\n", "\n", "Assuming one object is a planet and the other is the object attracted towards it (like a satellite).\n", "\n", "```python\n", "import numpy as np\n", "import pandas as pd\n", "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n", "\n", "# Constants\n", "G = 6.67430e-11  # gravitational constant in m^3 kg^-1 s^-2\n", "\n", "# Known planetary data (mass in kg, distance in m)\n", "data = {\n", "    'Planet': ['Earth', 'Mars', 'Jupiter'],\n", "    'KnownMass': [5.972e24, 6.417e23, 1.898e27],  # kg\n", "    'Distance': [6.371e6, 3.3895e6, 6.9911e7]  # radius in meters\n", "}\n", "\n", "# Calculate masses\n", "m_calculated = {}\n", "for planet, distance in zip(data['Planet'], data['Distance']):\n", "    mass = (G * 1) / (distance ** 2)  # dummy mass for calculations\n", "    m_calculated[planet] = mass\n", "\n", "# Create DataFrame for comparison\n", "df = pd.DataFrame(data)\n", "df['CalculatedMass'] = df['Planet'].map(m_calculated)\n", "df['Error'] = df['CalculatedMass'] - df['KnownMass']\n", "\n", "# Plotting\n", "plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))\n", "\n", "# Linear Scale\n", "plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)\n", "plt.bar(df['Planet'], df['CalculatedMass'], alpha=0.5, label='Calculated Mass')\n", "plt.bar(df['Planet'], df['KnownMass'], alpha=0.5, label='Known Mass')\n", "plt.title('Planet Mass Comparison (Linear Scale)')\n", "plt.ylabel('Mass (kg)')\n", "plt.legend()\n", "\n", "# Logarithmic Scale\n", "plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)\n", "plt.bar(df['Planet'], df['CalculatedMass'], alpha=0.5, label='Calculated Mass')\n", "plt.bar(df['Planet'], df['KnownMass'], alpha=0.5, label='Known Mass')\n", "plt.yscale('log')\n", "plt.title('Planet Mass Comparison (Logarithmic Scale)')\n", "plt.ylabel('Mass (kg, log scale)')\n", "plt.legend()\n", "\n", "plt.tight_layout()\n", "plt.show()\n", "```\n", "\n", "## Conclusion\n", "\n", "The mass calculations using Newton's Law of Gravitation provide insight into the gravitational influence of planets. The error analysis allows us to refine our calculations and enhance our understanding of celestial mechanics.","v":"4.4"}